  <div class="anat-framing">
    <div class="anat-framing-h">Read the Foundation carefully</div>
    <div class="anat-framing-body">The Foundation level has two halves that are easy to conflate. <strong>Some foundation elements HomeTest builds, runs and staffs</strong> (integration spine, framework instrument, IG framework structure, hazard log structure). <strong>Others are shared NHS services HomeTest plugs into rather than runs</strong> (NHS Login, NHS Notify, NHS App, FHIR routing). The first half is the BAU team&apos;s job to operate. The second half is the BAU team&apos;s job to interface with, govern and configure. The full ecosystem of consumed, regulated, contracted and served entities sits on the <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Ecosystem.html">Who page</a>.</div><div class="anat-framing-body" style="margin-top:12px;background:#EEF4FA;padding:14px 16px;border-radius:8px;border-left:4px solid var(--nhs-blue);"><strong>NHSE is a coordinating function and collective bargaining entity, not a direct buyer.</strong> The platform does not undertake direct procurement of tests or their logistics. NHSE sets the rules, holds the framework instrument, brokers relationships across the supply side (suppliers, pathology labs, logistics), and lets commissioner-to-supplier transactions run directly. This positioning is the architectural anchor for the Foundation. It is the line used externally (with Royal Mail and other partners) and it shapes how every Foundation element below is operated: rules-holder and broker, not transactor.</div>
  </div>

