        <div style="margin:8px 14px 0;padding:12px 16px;background:#FFF9EC;border:1px solid #F0DCA0;border-radius:8px;font-size:11.5px;color:#4C6272;line-height:1.55;">
          <strong style="color:#212B32;display:block;margin-bottom:4px;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:0.5px;text-transform:uppercase;">How to read the four columns</strong>
          <strong>HIV</strong> is live Beta in Salford and East Sussex (SH:24, Preventx). Solid commitment.
          <strong>PSA-AS</strong> is the Acute Use Case (clinician-init, Mark&apos;s journey). Design firm, deployment prospective.
          <strong>iron deficiency anaemia</strong> is Use Case 3 in the OBO list (GP-init, Layla&apos;s journey, focused on relieving GP pressures), design phase only; pattern picks are working assumptions and several entries say TBC because they genuinely are.
          <strong>Community / Pharmacy</strong> (previously labelled Pharmacy-init) is the fourth initiation pattern from the discovery taxonomy. The fifth canonical pattern, <strong>Programme / System initiated</strong>, is catalogued on the <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Pattern Overlay Detail.html#initiation" style="color:var(--nhs-blue);font-weight:700;text-decoration:none;">Initiation overlay</a> and on the <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Prioritisation Framework.html" style="color:var(--nhs-blue);font-weight:700;text-decoration:none;">HomeTest Prioritisation Framework</a> (medication-management tests, RA on DMARDs/steroids, HRT, GLP-1 monitoring). Not on the Year 1 OBO list. Shown as a sketch so the architecture has a slot if SLT decide to scope it in.
        </div>

        <div style="margin:8px 14px 0;padding:12px 16px;background:#FBEAF2;border:1px solid #E8D2DC;border-radius:8px;font-size:11.5px;color:#4C6272;line-height:1.55;">
          <strong style="color:#212B32;display:block;margin-bottom:4px;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:0.5px;text-transform:uppercase;">What's not yet positioned</strong>
          Scope items that have surfaced through review but haven't been placed in the model yet. Each needs an SLT or sponsor decision before it gets a home in the foundation, overlays, or patterns.
          <ul style="margin:8px 0 0 18px; padding:0; line-height:1.55;">
            <li><strong>Neighbourhood Health Centres.</strong> Could be a delivery channel (kit distribution / sample collection), a referral source (clinicians there initiate testing), or both. <em>SLT to confirm.</em></li>
            <li><strong>Adoption: where does it sit structurally?</strong> Adoption activity is being done through the Partnerships workstream, and is two-sided: customer-side partnerships (GIRFT, NHS Online, national programmes that drive demand) and supply-side partnerships (assuring labs, supporting capillary centres, bringing the right supplier mix to market). Customer success is a third dimension: making demand and supply work together once both are in the room. Adoption itself runs through early-adopter trusts that benefit commercially from being first movers (Royal Devon, Chel West): they build the capability, consult into other trusts, and become peer advocates. Peer-to-peer credibility carries further than central messaging. What hasn't been resolved is whether adoption appears as a named function in the operating model itself (an overlay, a foundation capability, a row in the RACI), or stays implicit inside Partnerships. <em>Decision: SLT to confirm whether to surface adoption structurally.</em></li>
            <li><strong>Mobilisation and "hearts and minds".</strong> Transformation requires people to change all of these: workflows, clinical assumptions, operating patterns, commissioning behaviours, patient interaction models, risk tolerance, even professional identity. Not soft work; core strategic infrastructure. The platform succeeds only if clinicians trust it, pathology networks back it, commissioners see value, suppliers believe the market is viable, patients feel safe, national programmes advocate for it, and Trusts see measurable operational benefit. <em>Currently flagged but not owned in the model.</em></li>
            <li><strong>Clinician workflow integration.</strong> Acute-initiated and GP-initiated patterns require ordering and result handling inside the clinician's existing EPR or clinical system, not a second screen. The genomics service learned this the hard way: a separate ordering UI added integration complexity and was unpopular with clinicians. Single integration into the clinical workflow is a hard design constraint for acute-init (Mark's PSA-AS journey) and GP-init (Layla's iron deficiency anaemia journey). The model accommodates it through the result-handling overlay, but the integration burden on the supplier and the platform is real and not yet sized.</li>
            <li><strong>Segmented strategic messaging.</strong> Different value proposition per audience (clinicians, commissioners, suppliers, patients, national programmes), not a single narrative for all. The model has not yet developed audience-specific articulation. <em>Owner: TBC.</em></li>
          </ul>
          <div style="margin-top:14px;padding-top:12px;border-top:1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.08);font-size:12px;"><a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Status.html" style="color:var(--nhs-blue);font-weight:700;text-decoration:none;letter-spacing:0.3px;">See all open items across the model &rarr;</a></div>
        </div>

<!-- Level 4 (bottom) - Configuration - split into HIV / PSA columns -->
        <div class="fls-level fls-l4">
          <div class="fls-head">
            <div class="fls-num">LEVEL 4</div>
            <div class="fls-name">Configuration</div>
            <div class="fls-tag">Real-world deployment: the eight picks combined into a working service. Different per condition.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="fls-split">
            <div class="fls-col fls-col-hiv">
              <div class="fls-col-head">
                <div class="fls-col-name fls-col-name-hiv">HIV</div>
                <div class="fls-badge fls-badge-live">Live</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fls-config-text">
                <strong>HIV live in two LA + supplier pairings.</strong> Salford LA with SH:24 and East Sussex CC with Preventx. Both sourced via NHS SBS Sexual Health Framework (Lot 1). Patient orders through the NHS App. The supplier fulfils end-to-end: kit dispatch, sample analysis, result return. Result back to the patient direct in the NHS App. LA-commissioned sex health service holds clinical oversight. UKAS-accredited lab. Per-completed commercial. Same pattern, two live instances.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="fls-col fls-col-psa">
              <div class="fls-col-head">
                <div class="fls-col-name fls-col-name-psa">PSA</div>
                <div class="fls-badge fls-badge-prospective">Prospective</div>
              </div>
              <div class="fls-config-text">
                <strong>PSA via acute trust + specialist lab.</strong> Consultant requests the test from the active surveillance pathway. Capillary draw at home. Specialist lab analyses; logistics split between the kit supplier and the lab. Clinician sees the result first, mediates, then shares with the patient. Acute trust governance. Activity-based commercial within the acute envelope. Not yet deployed.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

<div class="fls-foot">
          <strong>What the stack shows.</strong> Top down: Foundation (Level 1) and Overlays (Level 2) are shared across every condition. That's why those bands run full width. Pattern picks (Level 3) split into four columns because that's where the conditions diverge: HIV live, PSA-AS prospective, iron deficiency anaemia in design (Use Case 3), and Pharmacy-init as a working sketch from the discovery taxonomy. Adding a fifth condition adds another column at Level 3. Levels 1 and 2 don't change. Configurations (Level 4, at the bottom) are real-world deployments. They're what the stack builds up to.
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note" style="background:#F4F8FC;border-left:4px solid var(--nhs-blue);">
          <div class="fls-note-tag" style="color:var(--nhs-blue);">Build vs buy</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>The overlays are also where build vs buy gets decided.</strong> Each of the eight dimensions resolves into either a platform-build capability (the centre builds it once and every commissioner inherits it), a buy-from-market capability (suppliers compete to deliver it within the framework), or a local-system responsibility (the commissioner or Trust owns it). Initiation pattern, result handling and information governance lean toward platform-build (universal mechanics). Supply chain, commercial structure and tariff treatment lean toward buy-from-market. Sign-off route and accreditation bar sit with local systems or accrediting bodies. This is the level at which the BA + product owner work plays out: each overlay needs a build-buy-borrow decision before the platform requirements are stable. <em>That decision has not yet been made for every overlay.</em>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note" style="background:#FFF8E6;border-left:4px solid var(--amber-deep);">
          <div class="fls-note-tag" style="color:var(--amber-deep);">Sample-collection device constraint</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>Postal-return viability depends on the device.</strong> Transdermal sample-collection devices (Tasso+, Tap, Impress) do not fit Royal Mail Large Letter internal depth dimensions. Any configuration that selects a transdermal device cannot use Large Letter for return, which constrains the supply-chain pattern choice and pushes return logistics into a different size class or carrier route. Conventional capillary-draw and finger-prick kits fit Large Letter. The constraint is physical and lives at the overlay level, not at the configuration level: it pre-empts pattern selection wherever a transdermal device is the right clinical fit.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note">
          <div class="fls-note-tag">Note on initiation channel terminology</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>Patient-activated handed-out kits are a digital pathway variant, not the non-digital channel.</strong> Kits that are handed out in person (at a pharmacy, an outreach event, a community setting) and then activated by the patient online still run on the digital infrastructure. They sit inside the digital channel as a variant of patient-init. The true non-digital channel is telephony: a patient who phones in, never touches the digital surface, and has the test arranged on their behalf. That channel remains a separate gap to be designed for equity and for GDS inclusion, and should not be confused with handed-out kit variants.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note">
          <div class="fls-note-tag">Note on trend analysis</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>Longitudinal trend analysis is deprioritised for now.</strong> PSA values from capillary samples and from venous samples are not directly comparable, so presenting them on a single trend line carries a clinical safety risk: a patient could be reassured or alarmed by an apparent rise or fall that is actually a modality effect. The position is to research the comparability question rather than build trend rendering into the platform at this phase. Result handling continues to expose individual results clearly; longitudinal interpretation stays with the treating clinician until the research lands.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note" style="background:#F4F8FC;border-left:4px solid var(--nhs-blue);">
          <div class="fls-note-tag" style="color:var(--nhs-blue);">Test catalog: a named Foundation capability</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>The test catalog is a named platform capability, not a passive list.</strong> It is the assurance and discoverability surface for tests, providers, pathways and SNOMED codes. The 12-month feature set places test catalog configuration alongside a rules engine (driving which test fits which pathway and configuration) and a dynamic-app capability (screen sets per test, so each test surfaces the right patient experience without bespoke build). These three components together turn the catalog from a static index into an operational mechanism of the platform.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fls-note">
          <div class="fls-note-tag">Note on result shape</div>
          <div class="fls-note-body">
            <strong>Result shape is a condition characteristic, not a pattern.</strong> HIV gives a binary outcome (reactive / non-reactive). PSA gives a continuous numerical value, often interpreted in trend during active surveillance. Nobody picks a result shape; it's intrinsic to the condition. It does, however, influence which Result handling pattern is sensible (binary leans Patient-direct, continuous leans Clinician-first) and shapes the hazards loaded into the clinical safety case (missed positive vs range misinterpretation are different failure modes). The platform carries both shapes via FHIR Observation without modification; the variation lives in the patient-facing rendering and the hazard log content.
          </div>
        </div>
  

